  <text>
    <body><div type="letter">
      <p>Brighton</p>
      <p>My Dearest. The poor bird has had a singular adventure this morning, having been locked up in her cage, without either seed or water, &amp; nearly starved in consequence. I locked my door when I was going into my bath, &amp; by no means</p>
      <p>could it be opened when I wanted it. The whole of my small household was assembled outside my apartment, but to no purpose. They were obliged to get a ladder, &amp; Hewett proposed Joseph being let in by me at the window. As I could not make up my mind to have a tete-a-tete en disabille with Joseph in my bed-room in such a strange way, I was obliged to dress myself</p>
      <p>&amp; lace my own stays, besides putting the room in decent order, that I might receive this queer knight errant in a proper manner. This in addition to waiting an undue time for my breakfast, has sadly exhausted me since, though I did not feel it at the time.-- I did not much fancy Joseph's company at all in my room, &amp; was agreeably suprised by Hewett's coming up the ladder herself with</p>
      <p>the necessary instruments for opening the door. This evinced some courage I thought. While she was occupied on the door, Joseph brought me some coffee &amp; bread up the ladder, which I was delighted to swallow. Fortunately my room is to the back. As it was, our opposite neighbours stared, congregated, &amp; wondered. It would have been a comical adventure on the Brighton parade.</p>
      <p>Hester was excessively</p>
      <p>entertained. Had it been the baby's hour, I suppose he must have been introduced up the ladder.--</p>
      <p>Emily called on Hester yesterday, which I took to be a liberty in my house, since H had only called on her without leaving her name, &amp; I had not called at all.-- As I was out, I avoided seeing her. She has told Hester an abominable lie, denying having made at all since she came</p>
      <p>here, when the Hen had actually seen her, which she did not know. Emily looked dreadfully guilty &amp; said nothing, when H quietly told her she had been seen on such an evening.-- Hen &amp; I called today on her, but she was out. Miss Fortescue was not at home either.-- H thinks Emily is puzzled sadly to know how I regard her.--</p>
      <p>The weather is still windy, but today has been fine.</p>
      <p>Perhaps I may get a ride tomorrow.--</p>
      <p>I was delighted with ou letter, &amp; long for another. My own dearest mate, how ou little bird loves ou!</p>
      <p>Ou most affecte A A K</p>
    </div></body>
